"""Paraphrase variants — multiple phrasings of the same concept to improve retrieval recall."""
_PARAPHRASES=[
    ('How do I declare a variable in JavaScript?','Use `const` for values that won\'t be reassigned (most cases), `let` for values that will, almost never `var`. const + let are block-scoped; var is function-scoped (legacy). const x = 5; let count = 0; for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {...}. const can\'t be reassigned but mutable objects bound to const can still be mutated.'),
    ('What is delta time in game development?','Time elapsed since last frame, in seconds. Multiply movement by dt so behavior is frame-rate independent: pos += velocity * dt. Otherwise game runs faster on faster computers. Cap dt to avoid huge values on lag spikes (otherwise object teleports through wall).'),
    ('What is volatile in C and C++?','Tells the compiler NOT to optimize away reads/writes to this variable — value can change unexpectedly (hardware register, signal handler, another thread without atomic). Critical for memory-mapped I/O: `volatile uint32_t *reg = (uint32_t*)0x40020000;`. Does NOT provide thread synchronization in C/C++ — use atomic for that.'),
    ('What is the difference between MCU and MPU?','MCU (microcontroller): CPU + RAM + flash + peripherals on one chip. Small (KB of RAM), low-power, runs bare-metal or RTOS. Examples: STM32, ESP32, ATmega. MPU (microprocessor): CPU only, needs external RAM + storage, runs full OS (Linux). Examples: Raspberry Pi SoC, server CPUs. MCUs for embedded sensors/IoT/control; MPUs for anything needing a real OS.'),
    ('What is the walrus operator?','Python\'s := assignment expression. Assigns AND returns a value, so you can use the result in the same expression. Example: `if (n := len(data)) > 10: print(n)` — bind n once, use twice. Common uses: while loop conditions, list comprehensions where you want to compute once + filter + project. Don\'t overuse — clarity wins.'),
    ('What is mixed precision training?','Train using lower-precision floats (fp16 or bf16) for most operations while keeping master weights in fp32. Faster (~2x) and uses less memory (~half) on modern GPUs. PyTorch: `with torch.cuda.amp.autocast(): output = model(input)` + GradScaler for fp16 (handles underflow). bf16 doesn\'t need GradScaler. Standard practice for modern training.'),
    ('What is parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT)?','Train only a small subset of a large model\'s parameters while freezing the rest. Adapters, LoRA, prefix tuning, prompt tuning all examples. Result: 1000x less storage per fine-tuned variant (MBs vs GBs), faster training, less catastrophic forgetting. LoRA dominant: injects low-rank matrices into attention; original weights frozen. HF peft library implements all.'),
    ('What is SSRF (Server-Side Request Forgery)?','Vulnerability: user-supplied URL causes server to fetch it. Bad: localhost (access internal services), file:// (read local files), 169.254.169.254 (AWS metadata endpoint, gives credentials). Prevention: (1) allowlist allowed schemes (https) + hosts. (2) resolve hostname; block private/loopback IPs. (3) disable redirects. (4) network egress controls so server can\'t reach internal IPs at all.'),
    ('What is eventual consistency?','After a write, reads may briefly return stale data before all replicas converge. Update propagates everywhere eventually. Examples: DNS (TTL-bounded), S3 (now mostly strong since 2020), social media feeds, Cassandra. Design clients to tolerate: don\'t assume "I just wrote it so I can read it." Conflict resolution: last-write-wins, vector clocks, CRDTs.'),
    ('What is a correlation ID or request ID?','Unique identifier attached to a request as it flows through services. Lets you trace ALL logs/metrics/spans related to ONE user action across the stack. Generate at the edge (UUID per request), propagate via header (X-Request-Id), include in every log line. Without it, distributed debugging is a nightmare.'),
    ('What is cache locality?','CPU cache reads bring in a whole cache LINE (~64 bytes). Sequential access reuses the line — fast. Random access fetches new lines — slow. Iterating a packed array (numpy) is 10x faster than iterating a linked list of same size. Same for struct layout: pack related fields together (struct-of-arrays vs array-of-structs).'),
    ('What is backtracking in algorithms?','Recursive exploration of choices, undoing each choice when a branch fails or ends. Template: def bt(state): if done: record; return; for choice in choices: state.add(choice); bt(state); state.undo(choice). Use for: permutations, subsets, combinations, constraint satisfaction (N-queens, sudoku), pathfinding. Always undo (backtrack) so other branches can explore.'),
    ('What is the trapping rain water problem?','Given heights, compute total water trapped after rain. Each position traps min(maxLeft, maxRight) - height[i] water. Precompute maxLeft + maxRight arrays: O(n) time O(n) space. Better: two-pointer L+R tracking leftMax + rightMax → O(1) space. Move pointer with smaller wall — that wall bounds the water at its position.'),
    ('How do I solve three sum?','Sort array O(n log n). For each i: two-pointer (L=i+1, R=n-1) for pair summing to -a[i]. If sum==target: record + skip duplicates. If sum<target: L++. If sum>target: R--. Skip duplicates at i too. O(n²). Sorting is the unlock — converts triple-loop O(n³) brute force.'),
    ('What is the Result type or Option type in Rust?','Rust uses Result<T, E> for fallible operations (Ok(T) or Err(E)) and Option<T> for possibly-missing values (Some(T) or None). Forces handling at the type level — no nulls, no uncaught exceptions. The ? operator early-returns Err/None, propagating up. Replaces try/catch and null checks with compile-time-enforced patterns.'),
    ('What does the ? operator do in Rust?','Shorthand for "if Err return Err early, else unwrap the Ok value." Works on Result and Option. `let x = foo()?;` is equivalent to `let x = match foo() { Ok(v) => v, Err(e) => return Err(e.into()) };`. Massively reduces error-handling boilerplate. The .into() lets ? convert between error types if From is implemented.'),
    ('What is a Python virtual environment?','Isolated Python environment with its own site-packages and pip. Each project gets its own venv so dependencies don\'t conflict between projects. Create: `python -m venv .venv`. Activate: `.venv/Scripts/activate` (Windows) or `source .venv/bin/activate` (Unix). Install in venv, not globally. Use one venv per project; commit lockfile (requirements.txt or pyproject.toml + uv.lock) but NOT the venv directory.'),
    ('What is the singleton pattern?','Class that has only one instance globally. Implement by overriding __new__ to return the same instance, or via a module (modules ARE singletons in Python). Use for: shared configuration, connection pools, loggers. Often discouraged because: hard to test (global state), violates dependency injection, makes parallel use harder. If you must, prefer dependency injection of the single instance over global access.'),
    ('What is dependency injection?','Pass dependencies into a class/function rather than constructing them inside. Instead of `def f(): db = Database(); ...`, do `def f(db): ...` and have the caller create the db. Benefits: testable (inject mocks), composable (swap implementations), explicit (clear what a function needs). Done well, makes code dramatically more flexible.'),
    ('How do I find a memory leak in Python?','Use tracemalloc: tracemalloc.start(); ...run code...; snapshot = tracemalloc.take_snapshot(); for s in snapshot.statistics("lineno")[:10]: print(s). Shows top allocation sites. Also useful: objgraph.show_growth() to see object counts growing between checkpoints. Common Python leaks: circular references with __del__, unbounded global caches, threads holding references to large objects.'),
    ('What is a hash table?','Array of buckets indexed by hash(key) % size. To insert: hash key, store in bucket. Collisions handled by chaining (linked list per bucket) or open addressing (probe to next slot). Lookup is O(1) average if hash is good and load factor low. Resize when load factor exceeds threshold (~0.7) — doubles size, rehashes all keys. Worst case O(n) if all keys collide.'),
    ('What is dynamic programming (DP)?','Solving a problem by combining solutions to overlapping subproblems, storing each subproblem result once (memoization). Recognize DP when: (1) optimal substructure (problem decomposes into smaller of same type), (2) overlapping subproblems (same subproblem appears multiple times in naive recursion). Two styles: top-down (recursive + memo cache), bottom-up (iterative table fill).'),
    ('What is the difference between BFS and DFS?','BFS = breadth-first search, expands neighbors level-by-level via queue. Finds shortest path in unweighted graphs. Uses O(width) memory. DFS = depth-first search, goes deep before backtracking via stack/recursion. Detects cycles, computes topological order, finds connected components. Uses O(depth) memory. BFS for shortest unweighted path; DFS for structural questions.'),
    ('How does Dijkstra\'s algorithm work?','Shortest path in graph with non-negative edge weights. Maintain priority queue keyed on tentative distance from source. Repeatedly: pop closest unvisited node, relax all its outgoing edges (update neighbor distances if shorter via this node). Mark node visited. Continue until target popped (or queue empty). O((V+E) log V) with binary heap. Fails with negative weights (use Bellman-Ford instead).'),
]
LESSONS=_PARAPHRASES
